This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. Science fiction is written by people with
diverse backgrounds. The range covers the sciences, the humanities, and even the

00:50.140 --> 00:58.300
arts. Paul O. Williams, a 1982 Campbell Award finalist and author of four novels
so far in the Pell-Barr cycle, is an English professor at a small Midwestern

00:58.300 --> 01:06.960
university. Williams allows that his approach to science fiction is different
from that of most writers. I come at science fiction from a different angle from

01:06.960 --> 01:20.840
most people, out of much more of a literary background than most science fiction
writers, and particularly out of American lit. So I think my books tend to

01:20.840 --> 01:32.020
bridge the two types a little more than most books do. The novels of the Pell
-Barr cycle, The Breaking of North Wall, The Ends of the Circle, The Dome in the

01:32.020 --> 01:39.560
Forest, and The Fall of the Shell, describe America some 1,000 years from now in
the aftermath of a nuclear war. The descendants of the survivors have gathered

01:39.560 --> 01:47.380
into tribes with various lifestyles. Some are wanderers, hunter-gatherers much
like the American Indians. Others have built cities where they remain year

01:47.380 --> 01:55.480
-round. The city cultures are the most sophisticated societies, though they are
still quite primitive. At the time of the novels, Williams focuses on the Three

01:55.480 --> 02:03.440
River region a few miles north-northwest of St. Louis. The cities of North Wall
and Pell-Barr again lie along the present-day Mississippi. Animosity among the

02:03.440 --> 02:12.340
wandering tribes and the city dwellers is high. Skirmishes are frequent. We ask
Williams why he centered the saga around this area of the Midwest. I've lived

02:12.340 --> 02:26.060
here two miles downriver from where I put Pell-Barr again, now for 18 years, and
I'm utterly fascinated with this area of the United States. I think I became

02:26.060 --> 02:40.220
that way when I was way back in high school. I read Bernard DeVoto's book,
Course of Empire, which is mostly about the Louisiana Purchase and the move

02:40.220 --> 02:51.680
westward, especially Lewis and Clark in their expedition. And the place has
always had a sense of drama to me around here. And also, this particular area

02:51.680 --> 03:06.840
has a fantastic archaeological history. It's the one area in all of North
America that has the most, the densest Indian or prehistoric population. And

03:06.840 --> 03:22.500
I've done a good deal of study of archaeology, too. It just seemed like a
natural place to put a rather settled civilization, or culture, rather, and have

03:22.500 --> 03:31.060
these others impinge upon it. Individuals in the various tribes compose poems
and songs. We asked Williams if the lyrics which appear in the novels are his

03:31.060 --> 03:45.900
own. Yes, they're all original poems. And some of them are, you know, really
just quatrains or hymn stanzas. There's nothing terribly remarkable. I tried to,

03:46.400 --> 03:58.980
especially in the breaking of Northwall, use a variety of styles, inventing new
styles for each of the tribal groups, and that was kind of fun. Williams

03:58.980 --> 04:13.660
considers one of the poems to be serious. The most serious poem, I think, in all
three volumes is one that is sung near the end of Dome in the Forest. And that's

04:13.660 --> 04:21.560
actually a poem I've had around for years, and I think I kind of like it. It's
sung by a character named Tristal.

04:24.040 --> 04:35.640
A friend of mine told me the other day that she had just been divorced, and I
guess it was a friendly divorce or something, and she copied the poem and sent

04:35.640 --> 04:48.920
it to her ex-husband, which is kind of amusing to me. It's on page 211 of The
Dome in the Forest. It starts, Goodbye, My Favorite Stranger. I think that's the

04:48.920 --> 04:54.880
most serious poem in the three books. More about Paula Williams on our next
show.

