12:22.260 --> 12:30.240
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. In The Dome in the Forest, the third novel
in the pale bar cycle by Paul O. Williams, the primitive inhabitants of the

12:30.240 --> 12:37.280
American Midwest approximately a thousand years from now discover a
technological society that has existed underground since the nuclear holocaust a

12:37.280 --> 12:45.200
thousand years in the past. Technologically advanced, yes, but the Dome society
is bereft of feeling and intuition. In fact, Williams says the theme of this

12:45.200 --> 12:54.560
novel is the clash between an emotionally dead, technologically advanced society
and the primitive tribes. One of the main things I was trying to do in the book

12:54.560 --> 13:07.500
was to examine the difference between intuition and logic as means of human
understanding. And there are certain characters in the book, like Stale and Aro,

13:07.720 --> 13:21.300
and like Ruth Ann, who comes from the Dome and almost immediately marries a
character named Blue. They're people who combine, to a certain degree, feeling

13:21.300 --> 13:38.080
and thought or intuition and logic. And they very quietly succeed in advancing
their societies. But they're also extremes, as represented by Tor the Shumai as

13:38.080 --> 13:52.240
a man of incredible intuition. And Eelon from the Dome as a person of nearly
pure logic. And those two really ought to get together. But they sort of

13:52.240 --> 14:08.980
instinctively also distrust each other. And in the end, well, in the book, Pell
Baragin goes through a severe internal struggle as to whether to accept the Dome

14:08.980 --> 14:22.300
people into their society. And in essence, the struggle to me is whether or not
the society is going to turn from being essentially a religious society to being

14:22.300 --> 14:33.320
much more of a technological society. And they decide in favor of technology,
but it's not entirely a victory. Characters that are completely logical or

14:33.320 --> 14:44.840
completely intuitive do not thrive in a mixed society. As the book continues, we
see the logical people, the merely logical people, continually making gross

14:44.840 --> 14:59.620
mistakes. And the intuitional people, but particularly Tor, finding less and
less of a place in the central society of the Heart River, that is, Pell

14:59.620 --> 15:14.980
Baragin, and in the end, Tor and his nephew are sort of coughed up. They leave.
They go essentially exploring, which is what intuition tends to do. One is

15:14.980 --> 15:22.140
struck by the cover of the Dome in the Forest. The text actually describes it.
When we asked Williams if the artist had carefully read the book, then painted

15:22.140 --> 15:36.200
the cover, he told us this was not so. The Dome in the Forest cover, though, did
not really come about as you anticipated. It's kind of an odd story. Because

15:36.200 --> 15:46.480
when I was halfway through the book and I talked to my editor about what it was
going to be of life, he told me, we have this cover sitting around here and we

15:46.480 --> 15:58.900
don't know what we're going to use it for. Would you mind if I send it to you to
see if you like it for your book? And so he did. And I liked the cover very

15:58.900 --> 16:10.000
much. And so I actually wrote the cover into that scene near the end of the
book. Williams feels strongly that a culture can survive only if it nurtures

16:10.000 --> 16:19.440
social growth as well as technological advancement. That's what the Pell Bar
cycle is all about. In a sense, I'm trying through the series to indicate, I

16:19.440 --> 16:32.440
hope realistically, but to indicate anyway, that if social growth happens in
conjunction with technological growth, we're going to do a whole lot better than

16:32.440 --> 16:35.980
if we simply give ourselves to technology.

