18:07.980 --> 18:15.880
This is Daryl Ane. And David Carson. Many works of science fiction deal with
xenobiology, where life which has evolved somewhere besides the Earth. In the

18:15.880 --> 18:23.000
science fiction tradition, we have life ranging from lowly plant forms, which
yield pharmaceuticals or immortality drugs, to bug-eyed monsters with a taste

18:23.000 --> 18:29.860
for voluptuous Earth women. But what do scientists think about the possibility
of life on other planets? We asked Robert Forward, a practicing scientist and

18:29.860 --> 18:48.940
science fiction writer. The fact that the empty space between stars is full of
organic compounds, which just seem to be formed naturally by carbon and hydrogen

18:48.940 --> 19:02.980
and oxygen and a little bit of starlight and lots of time, sort of seems to me
that this stuff that exists out between stars ought to exist just as well on the

19:02.980 --> 19:15.200
surface of planets and so forth. And so I really firmly believe that there's
lots of life out there, because it just sort of seems to form naturally. And we

19:15.200 --> 19:24.220
have physical evidence of it from the molecular spectra we get, not from
planets. We don't have any evidence that there's any organic material on

19:24.220 --> 19:37.120
planets, except for one, ours. But we do have plenty of evidence there's lots of
quite complex molecular material in space, and so therefore, I mean, it would be

19:37.120 --> 19:44.720
begging the question to say that it doesn't exist on any other planet but ours.
Okay, so the possibility for life in the universe looks good. Then why haven't

19:44.720 --> 19:55.860
we been visited by intelligent beings which evolved elsewhere? If the universe
had a lot of intelligent species in it, most of them would be billions of years

19:55.860 --> 20:06.280
older than we are, because we are on, around, a second generation star. Our star
is made up of trash left over from exploding supernovas from the first

20:06.280 --> 20:16.640
generation stars. And if there were a lot of intelligent beings, they had
billions of years to sort of wander slowly at a snail's pace throughout the

20:16.640 --> 20:27.040
galaxy, and they should have been here a long time ago. And there's no evidence
for it. And we aren't finding signals. And so there's a good deal of speculation

20:27.040 --> 20:41.480
in the scientific literature right now that there is no other intelligent race
within this galaxy. We are the first. Does Ford believe we are alone in the

20:41.480 --> 20:53.840
Milky Way galaxy? I don't really buy the argument, because I much prefer to
believe that an intelligent being, say, a thousand or years or a million years,

20:54.400 --> 21:10.280
and especially a billion years older than we are, has better sense than to come
and say hello to us. And the reason for that is that what does a civilization

21:10.280 --> 21:22.840
that's a million years older or a billion years older than we are, what can they
gain from us? The only thing they can gain from us is to watch us as we develop

21:22.840 --> 21:35.700
to see if we develop in a different direction than they did and find something
new that they didn't find because they evolved from an intelligence viewpoint in

21:35.700 --> 21:47.860
a different direction. If they contaminated us with one single evidence, one
single clue that there existed a billion-year race, billion-year-old race out

21:47.860 --> 22:02.580
there, our present course of development would be immediately diverted to try
and track theirs. And we would miss whatever new that we might find. So there's

22:02.580 --> 22:14.080
a very strong reason for an intelligent, ancient intelligent species to leave us
absolutely alone, because otherwise we're of no value to them.

